%S A397456 0,7,37,255,1641,11609,86438,668765,5321039,43302932,359157555,
%T A397456 3026977951
%N A397456 Number of consecutive n-digit prime pairs with gap 6.
%C A397456 Pairs of consecutive primes (p, q) such that q - p = 6 and both p and q are n-digit numbers (i.e., 10^(n-1) <= p < q < 10^n).
%C A397456 Unlike counting all pairs with difference 6, this sequence requires p and q to be successive primes (no other prime exists between them).
%C A397456 For 2 <= n <= 12, a gap of 6 is the most frequent gap ("jumping champion") among all occurring gaps between consecutive n-digit primes. This empirical dominance is supported by the Hardy-Littlewood prime-pair conjecture, as 6 is the first even number divisible by the two smallest primes 2 and 3, which maximizes its constellation constant over this range.
%e A397456 For n=2, a(2) = 7. The 7 pairs of consecutive 2-digit primes with a gap of 6 are: (23, 29), (31, 37), (47, 53), (53, 59), (61, 67), (73, 79), (83, 89).
%e A397456 Pairs like (11, 17) are excluded because they are not consecutive (the prime 13 lies between them).
%Y A397456 Analogous to A070076 (n-digit twin prime pairs).
%K A397456 nonn,base,more,changed
%O A397456 1,2
